## Deployment Guide

### Step 1: Install Node.js

```powershell
# Download from https://nodejs.org/ (LTS version recommended)
# Or use winget:
winget install OpenJS.NodeJS.LTS

# Verify:
node --version    # Should show v18+ or v20+
npm --version     # Should show 9+
```

### Step 2: Install Python

```powershell
# Download from https://www.python.org/downloads/ (3.10+ recommended)
# Or use winget:
winget install Python.Python.3.11

# IMPORTANT: Check "Add Python to PATH" during installation!

# Verify:
python --version    # Should show 3.10+
pip --version       # Should show pip 23+
```

### Step 3: Install SoX (Sound eXchange)

```powershell
# Download from: https://sourceforge.net/projects/sox/files/sox/14.4.2/
# Install the Windows .exe installer

# After installation, add SoX to PATH:
# 1. Open System Properties → Advanced → Environment Variables
# 2. Edit "Path" under System Variables
# 3. Add: C:\Program Files (x86)\sox-14-4-2\

# Or use chocolatey:
choco install sox.portable

# Or use winget (if available):
winget install sox

# Verify:
sox --version
```

### Step 4: Install FFmpeg (optional, for audio format conversion)

```powershell
# Download from: https://ffmpeg.org/download.html
# Or use winget:
winget install Gyan.FFmpeg

# Or use chocolatey:
choco install ffmpeg

# Add to PATH and verify:
ffmpeg -version
```

### Step 5: Set Up the Project

```powershell
# Navigate to the project
cd d:\assistant\voice-coding-assistant

# Install Node.js dependencies
npm install

# Create Python virtual environment
python -m venv .venv

# Activate virtual environment
.\.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1

# Install Python dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **First-time model downloads**: On the first run, the following models will be downloaded automatically:
> - **Vosk model** (~40MB): `vosk-model-small-en-us-0.15`
> - **Whisper Small model** (~244MB): Downloaded by `faster-whisper`
> - **Silero VAD** (~few MB): Downloaded by `torch.hub`
>
> This may take 5-10 minutes on first launch. Subsequent launches load from cache.

### Step 6: Configure the API Key

```powershell
# Edit the .env file in the project root
notepad d:\assistant\voice-coding-assistant\.env
```

Add your OpenRouter API key:
```
OPENROUTER_API_KEY=sk-or-v1-your-key-here
```

Get your key at: [https://openrouter.ai/keys](https://openrouter.ai/keys)

### Step 7: Compile the Extension

```powershell
cd d:\assistant\voice-coding-assistant
npm run compile
```

### Step 8: Run the Extension in VS Code

1. Open `d:\assistant\voice-coding-assistant` folder in VS Code
2. Press **F5** to launch the Extension Development Host
3. A new VS Code window opens with the extension active
4. Look for **"$(mic) Voice Coding"** in the status bar (bottom left)

### Step 9: Test Voice Commands

In the Extension Development Host window:

1. **Quick test**: Open Command Palette (`Ctrl+Shift+P`) → "Voice Coding: Hello World (Test)"
2. **Single command**: Press `Ctrl+Shift+V` → Speak a command → Confirm
3. **Continuous mode**: Press `Ctrl+Shift+C` → Say "Hey Coder" → Speak commands
4. **Manual input**: Press `Ctrl+Shift+T` → Type a command

